{
  "text": "where \u0393(x) is the gamma function. The normalization factor ensures that the total power in the near-field is the same as in the previous sections, and as such, the definition of the beam radius R 0 remains the same. This is clear to see as if one sets the super-Gaussian parameter n equal to one, we retrieve the Gaussian near-field, and if we set n = \u221e, then we retrieve the flat-top near-field. Eq.24 is therefore a generalization of the previous near-fields. In practice, the near-field of the HPL may not be circularly symmetric and could be elliptical or rectangular depending on the amplifier geometry. We however limit the study to circularly symmetric super-Gaussian beams such that we can continue to use the Hankel transform in Eq. 6. In general, there is no known analytic solutions to the Hankel transform of Eq.24 so we rely on a numerical study in this section. Based on our previous methods, we will assume the far-field radius can be also be normalized to the same beam waist value, \u03be = \u03c1/w 0 . A typical HPL may have a super-Gaussian near field on the order of n = 2 to 5, the far-fields of which are given in Figs.5 and 6 for the first two modes. We also include the results for a near-field beam with n = 1 (Gaussian driver), and for n = \u221e (flat-top driver) for comparison. Again we assume no power losses from the focussing optic, therefore the power in the focal spot is constant from one OAM beam to the next. It is clear to see that as n increases, the focal spot intensity profile quickly converges to the result of an ideal flat-top beam (n = \u221e). From Figs. 5 and 6, it is also clear to see that super-Gaussian lasers with n > 3 can be well represented by a flat-top beam. As before, we want to find an optimal LG mode to simply represent each of the OAM beams at focus for various and n values. Using the relations given previously in Eq's.17 and 19, we can find the suitable values of \u03b3 and \u03b7 for the LG modes. We have removed the subscript from the \u03b7 Tables 2 and 3 , respectively, for the first 6 topological charges and for more useful n values. Table 2 . Optimal beam waist ratios \u03b3 of the first 6 numbers for Gaussian (n = 1), flat-top (n = \u221e), and useful super-Gaussian mode numbers. An example of optimized LG modes fitted to n = 2 super-Gaussian modes are given in Fig.5 . We find remarkable agreement between the fitted result and diffraction theory. From Table 3 we note that there are a few LG modes that have a scaling factor close to unity, for instance the mode that best fits the = 2, n = 3 diffraction result has a scaling factor of \u03b7 = 1.001. This is in contrast to the modes that were fitted to the Gaussian near-field focal spots that had scaling factors less than 0.5 for > 2. This method of LG fitting is therefore practical for super-Gaussian and flat-top driven OAM beams whereas the method outlined in [CITATION_1] may be more useful for describing Gaussian driven OAM beams where accurate representation of power in the focal spot is of concern. Otherwise, we find the present method to be superior for describing the peak intensity and general shape of the OAM beam at focus. Fig. 7 . Laguerre-Gaussian beams fitted to the exact diffraction result (dashed) for OAM beams driven by a n = 2 super-Gaussian near-field beam for = 0, = 1, and = 2 topological charges.",
